00:00:00.260 --> 00:00:05.140
&gt;&gt;Female presenter: Micah Sifry, author of
the new book "Wikileaks and the Age of Transparency."

00:00:05.140 --> 00:00:10.390
Micah Sifry is the co-founder and curator
of The Personal Democracy Forum, editor of

00:00:10.390 --> 00:00:16.270
its award-winning techPresident.com blog,
and a senior technology advisor to the Sunlight

00:00:16.270 --> 00:00:21.580
Foundation. He has written a number of books
and is a member of the board of the Consumers

00:00:21.580 --> 00:00:26.560
Union, also the adjunct professor at the political
science department at the City University

00:00:26.560 --> 00:00:31.880
of New York Graduate Center, where he teaches
a course called Writing Politics. Please welcome

00:00:31.880 --> 00:00:35.100
Micah Sifry to our stage.

00:00:35.100 --> 00:00:43.510
&gt;&gt;Micah Sifry: Hi. [clapping] Alright. Well,
thank you, um, thanks a lot, Kate. It's great

00:00:43.510 --> 00:00:50.059
to be here. It's always fun to be at Google.
Um. And I kind of was thinking uh as I as

00:00:50.059 --> 00:00:57.510
I headed down here, that, uh, it was particularly
right to be talking about this book at Google,

00:00:57.510 --> 00:01:03.289
given Google's own mission, um, to organize
all the world's information and and make it

00:01:03.289 --> 00:01:10.470
universally accessible. Um, I think the the
topic of transparency ought to be and probably

00:01:10.470 --> 00:01:16.480
is, ah, quite close to the hearts of of lots
of people who who support that mission. Um,

00:01:16.480 --> 00:01:22.860
so I'm hoping that, ah, we'll get a chance
to to um sort of engage in a little bit of

00:01:22.860 --> 00:01:29.320
a dialog about how you think about WikiLeaks
and how you think about the larger transparency

00:01:29.320 --> 00:01:37.100
movement as it relates also to what Google
does. Um, 'cause I think, uh, um, you know,

00:01:37.100 --> 00:01:44.530
we live in in a rapidly changing world and
a big piece of that change is is ah ah being

00:01:44.530 --> 00:01:50.409
fostered at places like this.
Um, I'm gonna start by actually talking about

00:01:50.409 --> 00:01:56.350
just two quick episodes that have nothing
to do with WikiLeaks. Um, and just to say

00:01:56.350 --> 00:02:02.990
I wrote this book, ah, very quickly, it's
not a big book. It's a little book. It's meant

00:02:02.990 --> 00:02:12.560
to be, uh, in some ways, a connect, a connect-the-dots
kind of book. Because when WikiLeaks happened,

00:02:12.560 --> 00:02:19.019
I thought while all this attention is going
to Julian Assange and Bradley Manning and

00:02:19.019 --> 00:02:24.550
there are all kinds of important questions
raised by ah what they've done, but um there's

00:02:24.550 --> 00:02:30.150
a danger that, you know, our media will just
obsess on, you know, the celebrity aspect

00:02:30.150 --> 00:02:36.980
of this and miss the larger picture. And the
larger picture is that what WikiLeaks represents

00:02:36.980 --> 00:02:45.319
is a symptom of a of a larger trend. Um, and
if Julian Assange and WikiLeaks didn't exist,

00:02:45.319 --> 00:02:50.510
um, sooner or later somebody would have done
this. The technology to do this, build the

00:02:50.510 --> 00:02:58.310
state list platform or multi-state platform
that's relatively free from state intervention

00:02:58.310 --> 00:03:04.939
to enable whistle blowers to post internal
documents, that this has been coming. Um,

00:03:04.939 --> 00:03:09.431
and I suspect a year from now we may not be
talking about Julian Assange anymore, but

00:03:09.431 --> 00:03:16.920
we will certainly be talking about this larger
phenomenon of user-generated transparency.

00:03:16.920 --> 00:03:20.659
Um, so I wanted to just start by by with two
quick episodes.

00:03:20.659 --> 00:03:26.079
The first one is, ah, is there anybody here
from Croatia? OK, so you've probably not heard

00:03:26.079 --> 00:03:32.549
of this story, um, so ah, one of the people
I profile in the book in the section about

00:03:32.549 --> 00:03:38.709
the international transparency movement is
a guy named Marko Rakar, who several years

00:03:38.709 --> 00:03:47.239
ago he had a printing business, um, and ah,
a tax auditor came to him and basically demanded

00:03:47.239 --> 00:03:54.980
a bribe, ah, in order to get a clean tax bill.
And Marko refused to pay the bribe and as

00:03:54.980 --> 00:04:00.340
a result this guy basically hounded his hounded
him out of business, drove his printing business

00:04:00.340 --> 00:04:05.760
into bankruptcy. And this was early in the
days of blogging and he decided to start a

00:04:05.760 --> 00:04:12.200
blog called Pollitika, which is sort of like
the Daily Kos. Uh, is it's one of these sites

00:04:12.200 --> 00:04:18.630
where you have uh anybody can create an account
and um participate, not just the blogger who

00:04:18.630 --> 00:04:24.630
started it, and it's evolved into the leading
political blog in Croatia, a country of about

00:04:24.630 --> 00:04:32.700
ah eight, seven, eight million people. Um,
it's probably got ah you know five or six

00:04:32.700 --> 00:04:39.010
thousand core contributors, um, and, you know
it's one of the top-read sites in the country.

00:04:39.010 --> 00:04:46.400
Um, and Marko is, is, uh, part of a generation
of people in Croatia who are trying to move

00:04:46.400 --> 00:04:53.660
that country from being very much an authoritarian
system to something that's more open and democratic.

00:04:53.660 --> 00:05:02.860
Um, two years ago somebody leaked him a database
of the entire, uh, voter file for Croatia.

00:05:02.860 --> 00:05:08.970
Um, Croatia has this weird circumstance which
is that it has more registered voters than

00:05:08.970 --> 00:05:19.340
it has citizens. Um, and that's partly a relic
of being part of Yugoslavia and that you know

00:05:19.340 --> 00:05:25.850
people you know the boundaries of Croatia
include people who, like, probably lived across

00:05:25.850 --> 00:05:31.800
the road from where the boundary was put,
OK, but ah the fact is is that they don't

00:05:31.800 --> 00:05:37.180
police registration very well and there's
a ton of corruption around voter registration

00:05:37.180 --> 00:05:44.210
because if you're, ah, well first of all you
get some benefits, ah, but more importantly

00:05:44.210 --> 00:05:50.750
local officials use it to cement their power.
So he got this database and he um had the

00:05:50.750 --> 00:05:57.240
uh wisdom to put it online in a searchable
way so that you could look up any village

00:05:57.240 --> 00:06:01.830
and any address and see how many people were
registered to vote at that address and people

00:06:01.830 --> 00:06:06.600
started swarming into this, on his site, and
discovered towns where like there'd be an

00:06:06.600 --> 00:06:11.870
address like ah you know the town of Dusina,
there'd be an address the equivalent of 0

00:06:11.870 --> 00:06:18.880
Broadway, OK, and it has 400 people registered
at it, OK? And what was quickly exposed is

00:06:18.880 --> 00:06:26.470
the fact that local mayors or local police
were letting people register at fake addresses,

00:06:26.470 --> 00:06:32.660
using their votes to stay in office in local
elections, right? So this is about keeping

00:06:32.660 --> 00:06:39.530
local power structures intact. Um, by posting
this database Marko set off a firestorm in

00:06:39.530 --> 00:06:45.450
the country. It was top headlines, in every
paper, on the evening news and it set off

00:06:45.450 --> 00:06:52.810
ah a debate which is now culminating in a
constitutional change that will prevent it

00:06:52.810 --> 00:06:56.790
anyone from being registered to vote in more
than one country. [laughter] Right, you're

00:06:56.790 --> 00:07:01.160
in Croatia, you can only be registered to
vote in Croatia. Um, so they're starting to

00:07:01.160 --> 00:07:08.650
fix their process.
More recently, um, I need to be careful about

00:07:08.650 --> 00:07:15.812
how I describe this, somebody posted a database,
and this one was not posted in in Croatia,

00:07:15.812 --> 00:07:22.570
it was posted in the United States, but in
Croatian of all the veterans in Croatia receiving

00:07:22.570 --> 00:07:29.250
veterans' benefits. [audience member chuckles]
OK? Um and there were something like 500,000

00:07:29.250 --> 00:07:34.381
names on the list. And to be a veteran means
you get like subsided health care, you can

00:07:34.381 --> 00:07:40.370
get, uh, you can buy imports without paying
high tariffs, ah you get cheap loans to buy

00:07:40.370 --> 00:07:45.530
a house. And there were more than 500,000
names on the list. The problem is, is that

00:07:45.530 --> 00:07:52.750
when the war, when the Balkan war ended, there
were only 300,000 veterans. The ruling party

00:07:52.750 --> 00:07:57.240
had been adding names to the list of whoever
they wanted to do a favor for and so they

00:07:57.240 --> 00:08:04.150
discovered when this list was posted that
there were politicians who had maybe, quote,

00:08:04.150 --> 00:08:10.000
"served a week" ah who were being listed as
veterans and getting these benefits. Um, when

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:16.250
this happened Marko was arrested. He was briefly
held, uh, by the police. They searched all

00:08:16.250 --> 00:08:22.840
his computers. Uh, they couldn't find anything,
luckily for him. Um and if you say to Marco,

00:08:22.840 --> 00:08:30.139
well ah nobody, you know, if you ask him who
leaked the databases, you know, nobody knows.

00:08:30.139 --> 00:08:34.640
If you say to him, well, nobody really knows
how the data was leaked, he'll say, "Well,

00:08:34.640 --> 00:08:45.900
actually it was on CDs" um, with a wink. OK?
I think of Marko as a data transparency revolutionary.

00:08:45.900 --> 00:08:50.700
Um, and I think there are lots of people like
him around the world. But I think it's important

00:08:50.700 --> 00:08:57.480
to ask a question about him. So the second
database, the one with the veterans benefits,

00:08:57.480 --> 00:09:02.580
that was posted on servers in the United States,
it actually, like, was hit millions of times

00:09:02.580 --> 00:09:08.590
in the first few weeks uh that it came out,
the demand from inside Croatia was so big.

00:09:08.590 --> 00:09:14.940
But what if, I don't know, let's say Croatia
was like a really close ally of the United

00:09:14.940 --> 00:09:22.180
States and some senator, you know, called
on the company that was hosting the servers

00:09:22.180 --> 00:09:29.080
to take it down because it was stolen material,
right, and then that company took it down,

00:09:29.080 --> 00:09:33.760
kicked them off their servers, what would
we think?

00:09:33.760 --> 00:09:41.430
Um, the second story I want to tell you is
about um the problem of, I guess, I guess,

00:09:41.430 --> 00:09:47.290
I would call this the problem of illegitimate
secrecy of when governments try to hide information

00:09:47.290 --> 00:09:54.350
that citizens know should also be let loose
into the world to, uh, expose and deal with

00:09:54.350 --> 00:10:01.790
corruption. Um it's the case of the British
Parliament, uh, expense records, people familiar

00:10:01.790 --> 00:10:09.640
with this story? Um, I mean for years uh,
a couple of journalists have been like foyering

00:10:09.640 --> 00:10:16.070
the British Parliament to release the expense
records and they've been just you know deny,

00:10:16.070 --> 00:10:22.370
deny, deny, drag their feet, um, after about
five years the Parliament, and exposure in

00:10:22.370 --> 00:10:28.800
other ways, the Parliament finally set up
a committee, ah, to start to release the records.

00:10:28.800 --> 00:10:35.410
Um, what they were really doing is they set
up a internal secret redaction unit to clean

00:10:35.410 --> 00:10:42.800
up the records before they were released so
nothing embarrassing would come out. So, ah,

00:10:42.800 --> 00:10:47.450
in May of 2009 the Telegraph, the British
newspaper the Telegraph, actually started

00:10:47.450 --> 00:10:52.830
publishing the unexpurgated records and they
were leaked to them by a a guy named John

00:10:52.830 --> 00:10:58.190
Wick who is a former SAS officer who is actually
the intermediary for an anonymous source.

00:10:58.190 --> 00:11:03.180
We don't know who that person was, we believe
it's somebody who was actually on the staff

00:11:03.180 --> 00:11:09.960
of this redaction unit. Um, and Heather Brooke,
who was the journalist who was doing all these

00:11:09.960 --> 00:11:15.210
foyer requests writes about this, she says,
"Some of the people on the staff of that unit

00:11:15.210 --> 00:11:19.970
were so disgusted by what they saw and by
the lies being told about the delays in releasing

00:11:19.970 --> 00:11:25.390
the information that they made a copy of the
data, a mole inside the redaction room made

00:11:25.390 --> 00:11:31.100
a copy, later passed it to John Wick." Wick
says that he also was told that critical information

00:11:31.100 --> 00:11:34.560
was being removed from the files that would
prevent many of the expense scandals from

00:11:34.560 --> 00:11:40.290
being revealed and he said to the, to the
Telegraph at the time, "The ultimate source

00:11:40.290 --> 00:11:45.451
was adamant that the key thing was that both
the information and the way in which it was

00:11:45.451 --> 00:11:49.490
handled should be in the public domain and
that its release was in the public interest."

00:11:49.490 --> 00:11:54.149
Wick also told the press he was personally
dismayed at how much information the government

00:11:54.149 --> 00:11:59.160
was collecting on the public and how poorly
it was keeping that information private, saying,

00:11:59.160 --> 00:12:03.020
"We've reached the stage in society where
they want to know everything about us, I think

00:12:03.020 --> 00:12:11.310
we're entitled to know about them." Now as
a result of this leak, again, it set off a

00:12:11.310 --> 00:12:18.990
huge bi-partisan or tri-partisan, uh, political
scandal in England. Uh, various people lost

00:12:18.990 --> 00:12:25.910
their jobs including the Speaker of the Parliament,
who's more of a functionary than he is a political

00:12:25.910 --> 00:12:32.529
figure but he was covering everybody else's
asses. Um, it also put, lit a fire under the

00:12:32.529 --> 00:12:37.810
open data movement in British government and
it's why a guy like Tim Berners-Lee has actually

00:12:37.810 --> 00:12:42.970
been able to get in and work with both first
the Labor Government and now more recently

00:12:42.970 --> 00:12:48.041
the Conservative Government on all the open
data stuff that the Brits have been doing

00:12:48.041 --> 00:12:53.040
which is actually uh at least as good if not
better than what the Obama administration

00:12:53.040 --> 00:13:00.330
has been doing. So here's a case where a leak
by a conscientious insider, uh, has really,

00:13:00.330 --> 00:13:05.960
um, had dramatically positive effects even
though it was extremely disruptive and embarrassing,

00:13:05.960 --> 00:13:12.190
um, to people in power.
So I, I wanted to open with both of those

00:13:12.190 --> 00:13:19.899
stories because I think they, uh, point to
the larger promise of the transparency movement.

00:13:19.899 --> 00:13:29.390
Um, which I think is both a top down and a
bottom up ah kind of thing. Um, the top down

00:13:29.390 --> 00:13:34.830
is from enlightened insiders who recognize
the power of open data and open information

00:13:34.830 --> 00:13:42.770
to make institutions work better and to enable
us, the citizens, to do things together and

00:13:42.770 --> 00:13:49.400
with government to make, ah, the whole civic
sector work better. Um, and it's also gonna

00:13:49.400 --> 00:13:54.860
happen from the bottom up with people doing
it to the powers that be.

00:13:54.860 --> 00:14:03.399
Um, how many people here know why Bradley
Manning said he, uh, leaked the stuff that

00:14:03.399 --> 00:14:08.589
he leaked, assuming he did indeed do it to
give it to WikiLeaks, which is alleged at

00:14:08.589 --> 00:14:15.010
this point, right? Anybody here know what
he, what the reasons are? So all we have right

00:14:15.010 --> 00:14:21.720
now are the chat logs that Adrian Lamo, uh,
leaked to Wired magazine and which uh have

00:14:21.720 --> 00:14:28.399
been posted, but in those, um and we also
have the back and forth between uh Bradley

00:14:28.399 --> 00:14:32.480
Manning and his lawyer, uh, and he has one
friend who's been allowed to visit him in

00:14:32.480 --> 00:14:37.820
prison. So there's been little bits of data
that have come out from that and so far there's

00:14:37.820 --> 00:14:42.500
been nothing to contradict, uh, what's in
those chat logs. And in the chat logs what

00:14:42.500 --> 00:14:51.331
he says is he was serving in Iraq on a military
base, um, and he was given the assignment,

00:14:51.331 --> 00:14:57.470
he was in a low-level intelligence job, and
he was given the assignment of looking into

00:14:57.470 --> 00:15:05.839
the case of 15 Iraqi insurgents who'd been
arrested by the Iraqi National Police. Um,

00:15:05.839 --> 00:15:11.240
and what he discovered, he says, is that they
had been distributing a leaflet critical of

00:15:11.240 --> 00:15:17.410
the Prime Minister Maliki. And the leaflet
essentially, after he got it translated, was

00:15:17.410 --> 00:15:23.430
titled something like Where Did The Money
Go? It was an anti-corruption pamphlet and

00:15:23.430 --> 00:15:29.019
it was dealing with publicly available information
raising questions about corruption inside

00:15:29.019 --> 00:15:37.420
the government. And, uh, he got upset because
he thought that we were in Iraq to actually,

00:15:37.420 --> 00:15:43.920
uh, help them develop a real democracy including
one that would ferret out corruption and wouldn't

00:15:43.920 --> 00:15:51.220
arrest people for spreading that information
and, um, so he went to his superior and his

00:15:51.220 --> 00:15:58.060
superior told him to shut up, do his job and,
if anything, find ways to help the Iraqi police

00:15:58.060 --> 00:16:07.050
arrest more people like this. That's when
he says he had an epiphany or crisis of conscience.

00:16:07.050 --> 00:16:11.480
I mean his words, I'm not using his exact
words, I did quote some of them in the book,

00:16:11.480 --> 00:16:18.430
but he says at that point he started seeing
things differently. Um, now I'm not gonna

00:16:18.430 --> 00:16:23.830
say whether or not it was the right thing
for him to leak everything, or you know, take

00:16:23.830 --> 00:16:29.660
a huge data dump, we could debate that, I
suppose. But I do really want people to understand,

00:16:29.660 --> 00:16:38.500
at heart, what Bradley Manning is, is a transparency
activist. OK? Um, and right now he has been

00:16:38.500 --> 00:16:45.019
in a U.S. prison, military prison in Virginia
going on nine months, more or less solitary

00:16:45.019 --> 00:16:49.720
confinement. The latest thing they've come
up with is to make him strip naked every night

00:16:49.720 --> 00:16:56.720
and show up each morning in front of his cell
naked because he apparently joked about the

00:16:56.720 --> 00:17:03.740
possibility that he could use the elastic
band in his underwear to cause himself harm.

00:17:03.740 --> 00:17:11.709
Um, that's happening right now in our country.
And I think he deserves his day in court.

00:17:11.709 --> 00:17:19.910
He may well have to spend a long time in jail
for violating the military code, but you know,

00:17:19.910 --> 00:17:25.170
don't we have a system here, rule of law,
people are supposed to get charged at some

00:17:25.170 --> 00:17:30.040
point and have a chance to defend themselves?
It's been nine months. So.

00:17:30.040 --> 00:17:36.650
Uh, that's it, that's my opening remarks,
um, I'm happy to take questions uh or just

00:17:36.650 --> 00:17:43.240
dive into the questions that are here. How
